<a href="javascript:card_browser(856)">Uruk Warrior</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(31)">Saruman&#39;s Ambition</a> x2    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> First of all, this deck is pre-rotel, and pre-erratum.  Since the recent errata of the mirror, it is almost impossible to ressurect this deck.  This deck is simply posted due to everyone and their mother asking me to post it, so here it is!<br>
<br>
The track record of this deck is rather insane.  The deck in this form (besides the countless small tournies it has won) has achieved the following:<br>
Origins, Day One Winner (Clint Hays)<br>
Origins, Day One (9th place) (Ben Lacey)<br>
Origins, Day One (21st place)<br>
Origins, Day Two (3rd place) (Clint Hays)<br>
Origins, Day Two (11th place) (Ben Lacey)<br>
Georgia TOC, First Place<br>
Arkansas TOC, First Place (Ben Lacey)<br>
Arkansas TOC, Second Place<br>
<br>
The White Arrows/Shoulder/Mirror Fellowship has several accomplishments as well:<br>
Tennessee TOC, 3rd Place<br>
Kentucky TOC, 3rd Place (Wess Victory)<br>
Alabama TOC, 1st Place (William Cruse)<br>
South Carolina TOC, 4th Place (Ben Lacey)<br>
South Carolina TOC, 5th Place<br>
Origins, Day One (3rd Place) (Clay Wilburn)<br>
Origins, Day One (17th Place) (William Cruse)<br>
Origins, Day Two (16th Place) (Clay Wilburn)<br>
DPC Atlanta, 2nd Place (Trevor Bradley)<br>
GenCon, 8th Place (William Cruse)<br>
<br>
***END TRACK RECORD***<br>
<br>
Me and some friends of mine used to drive up to Franklin TN to play cards with some locals around there, and one evening i saw star wars legend brian rippitoe playing a shoulder to shoulder deck that used reoccuring archery to move with the swiftness. little did brian know, he had stumbled onto something a little too good. the deck that brian was playing was built really bad (due to him actually having a life, and a girlfriend), so i took the idea and tried to build on it.  I built a deck that was more tuned and i added a few cards here and there to change the deck to suit my taste.  one night at the shop ben and i (who hardly knew each other then) played a game of cards. He was playing white arrows with lorien elves and elven bows. yet again, a good idea in a bad deck, hehe. so we started talking about the discard factor of the game and we spread our decks apart and helped one another. he told me to add white arrows, and i told him to add more allies to shoulder to. after this, ben and i start playtesting alot and trying other stuff. we really liked to whitearrows/discard deck, but we both agreed that it wasnt consistant enough.  the first big tourny of the year was DPC atlanta. at the warm up friday night ben and i both played shoulder/white arrows just for fun, because we had planned to play gandalf super fellowship the next day.  we both go 5-1 only losing to flukes, but we agree that the competition there is lacking, thus making us look good.  one thing that did catch my fancy though, is my 3rd game. at site 6 i had my opponent down to no hand and no deck.  so ben and i scrub at the tourny, and ray (bens brother)takes 3rd.  we lose our faith in gandalf and decide to work with this deck a bit. we both agree that the fellowship is rather fragile and it is better to use it to cripple other people&#39;s fellowships and win with the minions. ben plays sauron orcs and i play moria.  after months and months of playtesting the deck is doign really well, but it tends to lose about 20% of its games to other mirror decks that are designed to run to site 9.  now, i have about 100 ideas for decks a day, and about 1 out of every 1k are viable, but one night i hit the money. i suggested to ben uruk discard, in hopes of depleting their deck and running to site 9. this actually requires us to grow some balls and run our asses off with this seemingly fragile deck, and god we were wrong about the fragile part. after playing with the uruk/discard shadow side and winning a solid 95% of our games from moving to site 9, we realized how broken the fellowship really was.<br>
<br>
The idea of this deck (of course) is to deplete the opponents deck and move to site 9 via gift of boats. it uses reoccuring archery with orophin and rumil+legolas and seemingly endlesshimmerpoints to soak all the wounds. Burning through your deck is key. Discarding minions every turn (usually captains, i hate unique minions), and drawing 3 cards a turn with elrond lets you set up a shadow hand every turn witch makes most opponents a bit apprehensive when moving twice.  The deck is increadibly resciliant.  A good example is my game with andrew morris at the GA TOC. He was playing moria and he killed my legolas and gimli at site 5 via the balrog. I moved to site 6 with just frodo and the allies take some hits, and the next turn i gift of boats to site 9 for the win.  You would not believe how people are just sitting at site 8, waiting for their fellowship turn so they can just waltz into site 9, and not get another fellowship turn.  The deck is almost immune to the most common counters against allies (tower assasin) and large fellowships (enquea and savagery), which gives it the best chance against these counter decks.<br>
<br>
Please dont rate this deck based on the current environment. I know thror&#39;s map and mirror have been erratad and i know rare saruman tears this apart.<br>
<br>
Thank you everyone, and i hope to see you at DecipherCon<br>
<br>
-Efridge<br>
